---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does it cost to reroof a house in Toowoomba?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For a typical single-storey Toowoomba home with a 150–200m² roof, a full reroof generally runs $18,000–$35,000 in 2026. A tile-to-Colorbond conversion sits toward the upper end because the old tiles have to be stripped and disposed of (around $20–$50/m²) and new battens and sarking added. A like-for-like metal reroof is usually less. Two-storey, steep-pitch, complex or acreage roofs cost more. We give a fixed written price after measuring the roof, not a guess off the street." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I convert my tile roof to Colorbond?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "For many Toowoomba homes, yes. Colorbond is much lighter than concrete tile (easing load on framing stressed by reactive-clay movement), sheds water and hail debris faster, won't crack or delaminate with age, and modern wind-rated fixing to AS 1562.1 handles Darling Downs storm gusts well. Tile suits some heritage and streetscape-controlled homes and a restored tile roof lasts decades — so it's not automatic. We quote both a tile restoration/repair and a Colorbond reroof so you can compare the real numbers and lifespans." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long does a reroof take?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A straightforward single-storey reroof is usually 1–2 weeks weather permitting. Stripping the old roof, upgrading battens and laying sarking takes the first few days; the new roof goes on after that. We never leave a roof open overnight without it being made weather-tight — important during storm season when an afternoon supercell can arrive with little warning." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need council approval or a licence to reroof?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A like-for-like reroof is generally maintenance and doesn't need development approval, but changing roof material, pitch or structure can — and heritage or character overlays in some Toowoomba streets add controls. The work itself must be done by a QBCC-licensed roofing contractor (it's well over the $3,300 licensing threshold), built to AS 1562.1 with wind-rated fixing to AS 1170.2. We handle the compliance side and tell you up front if any approval applies to your job." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Roof Replacement & Reroofing Toowoomba | Tile to Colorbond"
  description="Roof replacement & reroofing in Toowoomba — full tile-to-Colorbond conversions and metal reroofs, sarking & batten upgrades to code. QBCC-licensed, AS 1562.1 / AS 1170.2. Free quote."
  canonical="https://toowoombaroofrepairs.com.au/services/roof-replacement/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Reroofing &middot; tile-to-Colorbond &middot; metal reroof</span>
      <h1>Roof replacement &amp; reroofing in <span class="accent">Toowoomba</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        When a roof is past repair &mdash; rust-perforated metal, delaminating
        tiles, rotten battens, or one leak too many &mdash; a reroof is the better
        long-term spend. We strip the old roof, upgrade battens and sarking to
        current code, and lay a new Colorbond or tile roof built for the Darling
        Downs storm season. ~$18K&ndash;$35K for a typical home. QBCC-licensed.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/" aria-label="Call us"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a free quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>What a reroof involves.</h2>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">

        <h3>When replacement beats repair.</h3>
        <p>
          We&rsquo;d always rather <a href="/services/roof-repairs/">repair</a> or
          <a href="/services/roof-restoration/">restore</a> a sound roof than
          replace it. But some roofs are genuinely finished: metal that&rsquo;s
          rust-perforated through the sheets and laps, concrete tiles that have
          delaminated and gone porous, battens that have rotted out, or a roof
          that&rsquo;s leaked in so many places that chasing patches is throwing
          good money after bad. At that point a reroof is cheaper over the next
          twenty years than the endless repairs &mdash; and we&rsquo;ll show you
          the photos that prove which camp your roof is in.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Tile-to-Colorbond conversions.</h3>
        <p>
          The most popular reroof we do. We strip and dispose of the old tiles,
          inspect and replace any failed battens, lay new sarking (foil insulation
          and a secondary water barrier), then fix a Colorbond roof in your chosen
          profile and colour. Colorbond is dramatically lighter than tile, which
          eases the load our reactive-clay ground movement puts on the frame, and
          it stands up to hail and wind better. A 150&ndash;200m&sup2; conversion
          is typically $25,000&ndash;$35,000 &mdash; the strip-and-dispose
          (~$20&ndash;$50/m&sup2;) is what makes it dearer than a like-for-like
          metal reroof.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Metal-to-metal reroofs.</h3>
        <p>
          Replacing a tired or rusted metal roof with new Colorbond is faster and
          generally cheaper than a tile conversion &mdash; there&rsquo;s less to
          strip and dispose of. We check the battens and structure, upgrade
          fixing to current wind ratings, and renew flashings, ridge and gutters
          at the same time so the whole system is new together. See our
          <a href="/services/metal-roofing/">metal roofing</a> page for profiles
          and detail.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Battens, sarking &amp; bringing it up to code.</h3>
        <p>
          A reroof is the one chance to fix what&rsquo;s under the roof, not just
          what&rsquo;s on it. We replace any rotten or under-spec battens, add
          sarking where the original roof had none (it improves insulation and
          gives a second line of defence against wind-driven rain and hail melt),
          and bring fixing up to <strong>AS 1170.2</strong> wind ratings for our
          region. The new roof is installed to <strong>AS 1562.1</strong> for
          metal or <strong>AS 2050</strong> for tile.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Licensing, approval &amp; insurance.</h3>
        <p>
          A reroof is far over the $3,300 QBCC threshold, so it must be done by a
          licensed roofing contractor &mdash; check the number on the free QBCC
          register. A like-for-like reroof is usually maintenance, but changing
          material, pitch or structure (and some heritage/character overlay
          streets) can need approval &mdash; we flag that up front. If the
          replacement is storm-driven it may be an insurance job; see
          <a href="/services/storm-hail-damage/">storm &amp; hail damage</a>.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why we don&rsquo;t cut corners.</h3>
        <p>
          The temptation on a reroof is to skip the bits no one sees &mdash; reuse
          marginal battens, leave out sarking, under-fix the sheets to save
          screws. We don&rsquo;t, because those are exactly the things that fail
          in the next big Downs storm and turn a twenty-year roof into a
          ten-year one. We keep the roof weather-tight every night it&rsquo;s
          open, fix to full wind ratings, and leave you with documentation for
          insurance and resale.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Where we work.</h2>
      <div class="areas-grid">
        <a class="area-pill" href="/rangeville/">Rangeville</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/centenary-heights/">Centenary Heights</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/highfields/">Highfields</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/wilsonton/">Wilsonton</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/glenvale/">Glenvale</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/toowoomba-region/">All Toowoomba Region</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Thinking about a new roof?</h2>
        <p>We&rsquo;ll measure it, quote tile and Colorbond side by side, and give you honest lifespans for each. Fixed written price.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/" aria-label="Call us"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a free quote</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
